<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
I have examined the holotype ♂ from Banka (not Palembang. Sumatra. as stated by de 
<bibRefCitation author="Selys Longchamps. E. d e." box="[367,454,1518,1545]" journalOrPublisher="Ann. Mus. civ. Genova" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" part="27" refId="ref300" refString="Selys Longchamps. E. d e. Odonates de Sumatra, etc. Ann. Mus. civ. Genova, 27, 1889." title="Odonates de Sumatra, etc" type="journal article" year="1889">Selys</bibRefCitation>
). and Selys' allotypeQ from Lahat. in Palembang; both 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[365,503,1551,1578]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">specimens</emphasis>
are in the Mus. Amsterdam. In the same collection is a ♂, also from Lahat, determined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Albarda. H" box="[883,1044,1585,1612]" editor="Veth's" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref119" refString="Albarda. H .. in Veth's Midden Sumatra. Nat. Hist. Afd. 5. Neuroptera, 1881." title="Midden Sumatra. Nat. Hist. Afd. 5. Neuroptera" type="book" year="1881">Albarda</bibRefCitation>
as 
<emphasis box="[1102,1340,1584,1611]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">parallelogramma.</emphasis>
I am unable to distinguish this male from Javan specimens in my collection. which do 'not differ in the shape of their anal appendages. I am deliberately of opinion that 
<emphasis box="[873,992,1684,1711]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">albardae</emphasis>
is the same species as 
<emphasis box="[368,606,1717,1744]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">parallelogramma.</emphasis>
and that the differences ly within the range of individual variation.
</subSubSection>
